==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{m|fro|repeler}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|rapeler||to call back, call in, call after, revoke}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|repellō||drive or thrust back}}, from {{m|la|re-}} and {{m|la|pellō||push or strike}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ɹəˈpiːl/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-repeal.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|iːl|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cancel]], [[invalidate]], [[annul]].
#: ''to '''repeal''' a law''
# To recall; to summon (a person) again.
#* Shakespeare
#*: The banished Bolingbroke '''repeals''' himself, / And with uplifted arms is safe arrived.
# To suppress; to repel.
#* Milton
#*: Whence Adam soon '''repealed''' / The doubts that in his heart arose.

